observations.recommendation:
We recommended management the following:

Direct the Municipal Assessor to prepare the assessment roll containing a list of all persons whose real properties have been newly assessed or reassessed and the values of such properties on or before the thirty-first (31st) day of December each year, starting CY 2023;

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to maintain Real Property Tax Account Register/Taxpayer’s index card as basis for the recording of Real Property Tax Receivable and Special Education Tax Receivable;

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to maintain a readily available monitoring flatform for the collection of real property tax and special education tax;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to make a thorough analysis on Real Property Tax Receivable and Special Education Tax Receivable and come up with a subsidiary ledger schedule showing the details on a yearly basis; and

Direct the Municipal Accountant to prepare the necessary adjusting entry to correct the understatement of Real Property Tax Receivable and overstatement in Special Education Tax Receivable.

We recommended management the following:

Direct the Municipal Accountant to reclassify the claims of various officers and employees to Due to Officers and Employees account;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to conduct a thorough analysis on the item Listed as “Others” to determine whether the same shall qualify as part of the accounts payable based on the recognition criteria for liabilities, otherwise cause the necessary adjustment;

Moving forward, direct the Municipal Accountant to exercise due professional care in the recording of account payable taking into consideration the completeness and propriety of supporting documents; and

Direct the Municipal Accountant to incorporate the separate schedule prepared in the notes to the financial statements and provide other relevant information as deemed necessary.

We recommended management the following:

Direct the Municipal Accountant to conduct a thorough analysis on the discrepancy noted between the balance per general ledger and balance presented as book balance in the BRS and prepare the corresponding adjusting entry to record the reconciling items identified thereafter;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to make the necessary communication to the Land Bank of the Philippines – Buug Branch relative to the dormant account for its reactivation and make the necessary for bank statement thereafter; 


Direct the Municipal Treasurer to submit the corresponding disbursement vouchers together with its supporting documents relative to the unrecorded disbursement under bank account number 2852-1028-48 in the total amount of 340,462.87;

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to submit the corresponding disbursement vouchers together with its supporting documents relative to the unrecorded disbursement under bank account number 2852-1032-91 in the total amount of 11,417,735.39; and

Moving forward, direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that all reconciling items identified during the preparation of BRS shall be recorded in a timely manner.

We recommended management the following:

Direct the Municipal Accountant to make the necessary adjustment to correct the erroneous entry made to close the related income account to government equity;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to modify the subsidiary ledger by year to monitor the corresponding disbursement, if any;

Moving forward, direct the Municipal Accountant to provide the necessary disclosures in the notes to the financial statement relative to the Trust Liabilities – Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Fund account; and

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to ensure the actual transfer of unexpected DRRM fund to the trust fund account at the close of the year.

We recommended management the following:

Direct the personnel in-charge in the preparation of remittances to financial institution to trace whom the over remittances were made;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to reclassify the debit balance of other payable totaling ₱5,876.50 to its proper account Due from Officers and Employees;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to reclassify the amount due to DSWD relative to the Poverty Alleviation Program (SEA Loan); the 20% share for the Tuition Fee relative to the operation of WMSU – ESU Diplahan Campus; and the collection arising from the sale of bid documents amounting to ₱460,710.65, ₱994,896.87 and ₱946,086.13 respectively to trust liabilities;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to undertake a thorough analysis in coordination with the concerned offices relative to the cash balance of trust receipts.

The Municipal Treasurer to expediate the processing of documents needed to support the receipt of the donated property;

The Municipal Accountant to prepare the necessary journal entry to recognize the transfer of assets from the DPWH and PLGU Sibugay in the books of accounts of the LGU; and

Further, depreciate retrospectively the PPE from the moment of receipt of the assets and not during recording of the assets.

The Municipal Treasurer to conduct the physical inventory of the Biological Asset;

The Municipal Accountant to reclassify the account to the proper asset account and to reconcile with the records of the Municipal Treasurer; and

Moving forward, with the implementation of the Government Accounting Manual for LGUs, Biological Assets transactions are to be recorded in accordance with Sections 304 to 315.

Management to strictly enforce the liquidation of all cash advances for travel within thirty (30) days upon return to permanent official station and for cash advances for operating expenses within twenty (20) days after the end of the year in adherence to applicable rules and regulations in the grant, utilization and liquidation of cash advances;

Require the Accountable Officer relative to the cash advance granted for operating expenses to prepare the report of disbursements within 5 days after the end of each month and submit the same with duly accomplished vouchers/payrolls and supporting documents to the Municipal Accountant; and

Demand letter be sent to Accountable Officer for the immediate liquidation and settlement of all cash advances outstanding as of December 31, 2020 from concerned officials and employees including the suspension of salaries.

Creation of an Inventory Committee composed of adequate number of members to be able complete the physical inventory in three months or less. The committee shall also have at least one member each from the Accounting and Property Divisions/Units;

The Inventory Committee to conduct inventory taking activities in accordance to the approved Physical Inventory Plan (PIP) and prepare the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) upon completion of the physical count, using the prescribed format under the Accounting Manual and submit the same not later than January 31 of the ensuing; 

Moving forward, with the implementation of the Government Accounting Manual for LGUs volume II to follow the prescribed forms and reports described in sections 61 to 74 as illustrated in Appendices 54 to 67 of the manual. And to submit the same in accordance with GAM for LGUs volume I, section 266 not later than January 31 of the ensuing year;

The Property Unit and Accounting Unit to undertake collaborative procedures ensuring that all PPEs included in the RPCPPE are duly recorded in their respective records and that the Property Cards (PCs) maintained by the Property Unit and the PPE Ledger Cards (PPELCs) maintained by the Accounting Unit are reconciled; and

The management to undertake disposition procedures for non-existing/missing PPEs and derecognition procedures of non-existing/missing PPE without available record of accountability as provided for in COA Circular No. 2020-006.

Institutionalization of GAD database with adequate and systematic age and sex disaggregated data which will provide the bases for gender analysis, planning, programming and policy formulation; 

Undertake gender analysis to identify and confirm existing gender issues and ensure that the programs, projects and activities are responsive to the said issues; and 

Revisit Annex B of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-01, which identifies the data requirements for particular gender issues.

Adherence with the timeline in preparing the SEF budget;

The Local School Board to meet at least once a month with its members to address issues pertaining to education system in the public sector for the formulation of the priority program and projects enumerated under JC No. 01; and

Inclusion of program and projects for Early Childhood Care and Development (ECCD).

The Municipal Accountant to consider the asset recognition principle in recording procurement made by the municipality, where an asset should be recognized when it is probable that future economic benefit will flow to the enterprise or agency and it can be measured reliably;

The Municipal Accountant to make the necessary adjusting entries to properly classify the accounts to come up with reliable financial statements;

Recording of expenditures shall only be made upon issuance of supplies and materials as provided in Section 121 of the NGAS Manual; and 

Moving forward to the issuance of the Government Accounting Manual for LGUs, to strictly follow the provisions for recording of inventories as provided under Sections 175 to 207 and Sections 208 to 271 in recording Property, Plant and Equipment.

The Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to review prior years’ records and identify the payees in order for Management to notify the payees of the stale checks of the status thereof, and take other possible actions such as cancellation or replacement of the subject check;

The Municipal Accountant to draw the necessary Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) to appropriately record the cancellation of the stale checks; and

Moving forward, with the issuance of the Government Accounting Manual for LGUs to strictly follow the provisions for reporting of checks issued as provided under Section 79, Volume I and the accounting treatment/ procedures for spoiled / stale checks as provided under Section 104, Volume I.
